## Migration Analysis

**Pattern identified: Timeout enforcement** â€” a thread runs work and is forcibly aborted if it exceeds a time limit.

### Why this breaks on .NET 8

- `Thread.Abort()` â†’ throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (SYSLIB0006)
- `Thread.ResetAbort()` â†’ also throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`
- `ThreadAbortException` â†’ never thrown by the runtime

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException if the
            // token fires before the task completes.
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### Key pitfalls for this migration

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Work doesn't actually stop** | `CancellationToken` is cooperative. If `work()` is a long CPU-bound call that never checks the token, it keeps running on the thread pool after the timeout â€” you just stop *waiting*. The original `Thread.Abort` would forcibly kill it. |
| **Leaking `CancellationTokenSource`** | Always wrap in `using`. Leaking it causes timer leaks from `CancelAfter`. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | The `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` guard ensures you only catch your own timeout, not an unrelated cancellation. |
| **Truly uncooperative code** | If `work()` calls blocking I/O or third-party code that can't accept a token, the only way to forcibly stop it is to run it in a **separate process** and use `Process.Kill`. |

### If `work` can cooperate (preferred)

Change the signature to accept a token so work can actually stop:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    try
    {
        var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);
        return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Caller example:
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

This is the **correct** long-term fix â€” every long-running method in the chain should accept and forward the `CancellationToken`, with `ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at regular checkpoints.
